<br>
Like everything is static in EQ.  What besides the sleeper actually changes forever?  Not much, if anything else.  I'm hoping to find a game where my roleplay will make a difference in the WORLD, not just my small group of friends. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/umaladominus.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Maladominus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Ak'Anon Sex Symbol</span><br>  Posts: 599<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/11/02 7:02:59 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=443.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: NeverWinterNights</span><hr size=1> There is absolutely no reason why persistent  24-7 worlds cannot succeed in NeverwinterNights.  The main factors will be: <br>
<br>
1) how dedicated and competent is the server owner (the DM who created the world)? <br>
<br>
2) how stable is the host server? <br>
<br>
3) how good is the dedicated staff of volunteer DMs that will stick around to support and maintain that persistent world 24 hours a day, 7 days a week? <br>
<br>
<br>
NeverwinterNights: The Cabilis Project anyone? <br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ukurley.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kurley</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 99<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/11/02 11:10:35 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=443.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: NeverWinterNights</span><hr size=1> As far as persistent world go, there is a very large NWN project called A Land Far Away (ALFA) whereby the Forgotten Realms has been broken up into areas, with each area being run by a DM and assistant DMs with one or more servers.  The servers all have to pass a screening process (connection speed, stability, etc.) and currently there are something like 79 servers within the server ring.<br>
<br>
The DM's of the ALFA community have weekly chat sessions to hammer out consistent rules for each server and discuss the various facets of their &quot;world&quot;.<br>
<br>
Currently, Bioware has stated that a maximum of 64 players can be on one server at a time...however with 60+ servers, that translates into a LOT of room for players.  Even with EQ, when you start getting over 40 players in a zone, the client begins to take a performance hit.<br>
<br>
NWN was not designed to create a &quot;perpetual world&quot; in the same vein as EQ - the game rules and server to server dynamics are not as &quot;fluid&quot; as EQ or other commerically run MMORPG's are.  However, the NWN community has already shown immense interest, dedication and talent for fixing perceived problems with the NWN toolset as well as using innovative means to make things happen (be it by reskinning tilesets, redesigning in game graphics, or writing scripts).<br>
<br>
Want an example?  Some ingenious fellow scanned pictures of all of his coworkers' faces, and then using a very simple process involving Photoshop, replaced the &quot;out of the box&quot; faces of orcs with his coworkers.  He then wrote a number of scripts for this interesting clan of orcs whereby various individual members of the orc clan interact on a daily basis, and go about their daily routines.  The scripting can be as detailed as when two orcs meet on a pathway, they'll stop and &quot;chat&quot; for a bit, using various emotes and text to &quot;discuss&quot; local gossip.  <br>
<br>
And the real benefit is:  if you aren't very good at scripting or creating artwork, within a short time, customized, user created content will be available for everyone to download, use and modify.  This extends to reskinned tiles, customized items, scripts, creatures, encounters...<br>
<br>
I've been gaming for far too long, and NWN is simply the most powerful and user empowing piece of gaming material designed to date.  When you boil it down, EQ is a fantasy combat simulator, with a high degree of social interaction and competition.  NWN on the other hand, is a fantasy ROLEPLAYING simulator, where the users themselves can dictate what they want to play, and with whom they want to play it.<br>
<br>
